<A ID="p9x"></A>where Chrysippus calls the <I>Gastrology</I> of Archestratus a "metropolis" of the philosophy of Epicurus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note6" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">6</A>
<I>i.e.</I> worthy to be the subject of speech. <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἀξιόλογος</SPAN> is a favourite word of Diodorus in the usual meaning of "distinguished," "notable."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note7" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref7
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">7</A>
Of the writers who may be said to have composed universal histories, Diodorus may have had in mind Herodotus, who had no chronological system, Anaximenes of Lampsacus, who confined his <I>Hellenica</I>, as the title shows, to the Greeks, and Ephorus of Cyme, who omitted the mythological period and


<A ID="p15x"></A>whose death brought his history to a close with the year 340 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, although he had witnessed the stirring events of the subsequent twenty years.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note8" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">8</A>
The Diadochi, or Successors, were those rulers who shortly after 323 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> formed separate kingdoms out of the territory conquered by Alexander. The Epigoni were the next and succeeding generations.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note9" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref9
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">9</A>
On the travels undertaken by Diodorus in preparation for the writing of his history, see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/Introduction*.html#Diodorus_travels
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
the Introduction, p. xiii</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note10" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">10</A>
The prevailing language in Sicily in this period was Greek. On the acquaintance of Diodorus with Latin see
	<A HREF="
