<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note12" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref12
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">12</A>
On these periods and dates, as given more fully in the following paragraph, see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/Introduction*.html#scope_of_the_History
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
the Introduction, p. xv</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note13" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref13
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">13</A>
A philosopher and historian of the second century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> whose <I>Chronology</I> covered the years 1184‑119 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> The <I>Chronology</I> of Castor of Rhodes, of the first century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, which came down to 60 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, and was probably also used by Diodorus after the date where Apollodorus stopped, included the period before the Trojan War.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note14" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref14
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">14</A>
In
Book 40.8<!--</A>DIODORUS40--> Diodorus remarks that some of his Books had been circulated before the publication of the work as a


<A ID="p3x"></A>whole. Whether they had been materially altered, as was often done by the diaskeuasts, is not known.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note15" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref15
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">15</A>
That the universe, as well as the earth and the human race, was eternal was the view of Aristotle and the early


<A ID="p25x"></A>Peripatetics, and was defended by Theophrastus against Zeno, the founder of the Stoic school. The arguments used by Theophrastus are found in Philo Judaeus, <I>De aeternitate Mundi</I>, especially chaps. 23‑27; cp. E. Zeller, <I>Aristotle and the Earlier Peripatetics</I> (Eng. transl.), 2 pp380 f.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note16" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref16
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">16</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#10.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 10.2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note17" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">17</A>
Frg. 488, Nauck.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note18" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref18
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">18</A>
G. Busolt, "Diodor's Verhältniss z. Stoicismus," <I>Jahrb. cl. Phil.</I> 139 (1889), 297 ff., ascribes to Posidonius most of the Preface of Diodorus, but finds in this and the preceding


<A ID="p29x"></A>chapter Epicurean influence. The fact is that Diodorus' philosophy, if he may be said to have had any, was highly eclectic.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
