"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
Not the present Red Sea, but the Persian Gulf and the Indian Ocean.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
The Egyptian beer, called below <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">zythos</SPAN>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1B*.html#34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(chap. 34)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A>
Antaeus was a giant of Libya, the son of Poseidon and earth, who was slain by Heracles (cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/4B*.html#17.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Book 4.17.4</A>). According to one version of the story he received strength


<A ID="p67x"></A>whenever he touched his mother Earth and Heracles overcame him only by holding him in the air.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1D*.html#84
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chaps. 84 f.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A>
Though the island of Philae, once "the pearl of Egypt," was a sacred place of early Egypt, the beautiful temples which


<A ID="p69x"></A>have made it so famous were constructions of the Ptolemies of the last two centuries <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> and of the Roman emperors of the first three Christian centuries. Since the height of the Aswan dam has been increased the temples are completely submerged except during July-October.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
P. Foucart (<I>Le Culte de Dionysos en Attique</I>) maintained the Egyptian origin of the rites of Dionysus, but his view was strongly opposed by L. R. Farnell (<I>the Cults of the Greek City States</I>, 5 pp174 ff.).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
Dionysus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A>
<I>i.e.</I>, an appearance in the flesh of a deity. Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/2B*.html#47.6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Book 2.47.6 f.</A>, where it is related that Apollo visited the Hyperboreans every nineteen years at the time of the vernal equinox.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>
The Pillars of Heracles are described in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/4B*.html#18.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Book 4.18.4‑7</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A>
Heracles, according to Greek mythology, was a contemporary of Laomedon, the father of Priam king of Troy, and with the help of Poseidon built for him the walls of Troy.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A>
Alcaeus was the name of the grandfather of Heracles. The career of Heracles is recounted in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/4B*.html#9
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Book 4.9 ff.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note50" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref50
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">50</A>
The date of Matris, who was the author of an encomium upon Heracles, is unknown.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note51" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref51
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">51</A>
A reference to the common practice of incubation, briefly described below. The patients spent the nights in the temple-precincts and were ministered to in their sleep by the god. An interesting picture of such an incubation is in


<A ID="p81x"></A>Aristophanes, <I>Plutus</I>, 659 ff., where a description is given of how the god of wealth, who because of his blindness distributes his gifts with little discrimination, is taken to the temple of Asclepius to be healed.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note52" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref52
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">52</A>
Under the influence of the Ptolemies, soon after 300 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, the cult of Isis began to spread over the Mediterranean, and by the time of Diodorus was in practically every city of any importance.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note53" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref53
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">53</A>
"Records of the seasons." This designation for yearly records was used, for instance, by the inhabitants of the island of Naxos.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note54" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref54
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">54</A>
But the Giants of Greek mythology were represented with "huge," not "many," bodies.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note55" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref55
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">55</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
https://www.newadvent.org/bible/gen006.htm#4
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Bible)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Genesis</I> 6.4</A>: "There were giants in the earth in those days; and also after that, when the sons of God came in unto the daughters of men, and they bare children to them, the same became mighty men, which were of old, men of renown."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note56" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">56</A>
Cp. Sophocles, <I>Oedipus at Colonus</I>, 337 ff.:

<DIV ALIGN="center"><TABLE CLASS="verse">
	<TR>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="verse2">
Their thoughts and actions all
			<P>
Are framed and modelled on Egyptian ways.
			<P>
For there the men sit at the loom indoors
			<P>
While the wives slave abroad for daily bread.
			<P CLASS="signature">
(Tr. by Storr, in <I>L. C. L.</I>)
		</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note57" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref57
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">57</A>
Here some <SPAN CLASS="small">MSS.</SPAN> add the following sentences (cp. critical note), which are taken almost bodily from
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#22.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 22.2‑6</A>: "And they say that Isis is buried in Memphis, where her tomb is pointed out to this day in the temple-area of Hephaestus. According to some writers, however, the bodies of these gods [rest in Philae on the island in the Nile, as I have already stated] rest on the border between Ethiopia and Egypt, on the island in the Nile which lies near Philae, but is referred to because of this burial as the Holy Field. In proof of this they point to the tomb which was constructed for Osiris on this island and is honoured in common by all the priests of Egypt; and they mention three hundred and sixty libation bowls which are placed around it; for the priests appointed over these bowls fill them each day with milk, singing all the while a dirge in which they call upon the names of these gods. It is for this reason that only the priests are allowed to set foot on this island. And all the inhabitants of the Thebaid, which is the oldest portion of Egypt, hold it to be the strongest oath when a man swears 'by Osiris who lieth in Philae.' "

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify small italic">
The critical note to the Greek text, a long one, adds the additional text given by various family of manuscripts, without commentary.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note58" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref58
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">58</A>
According to Pseudo-Eratosthenes (<I>Catasterismus</I>, 33) the star on the head of Canis Major was called Isis as well as Sirius.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: See also
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Isis_and_Osiris*/B.html#T359d
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>de Iside</I> 359<SPAN CLASS="small">D</SPAN></A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Topics/astronomy/_Texts/secondary/ALLSTA/Canis_Major*.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Allen's Star Names, <I>s.v.</I> "Canis Major", <I>passim</I></A>, may be useful as well.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note59" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref59
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">59</A>
The Danube.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note60" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A>
This may be drawn from the Orphic legends which conceived of the undeveloped universe as a mystic egg, from which came Phanes, the first principle of life. Cp. the parody of the Orphic cosmogony in Aristophanes, <I>The Birds</I>, 693 ff.:
<DIV ALIGN="center"><TABLE>
	<TR>
		<TD><DIV CLASS="verse">
			<P>
			<A ID="p89x"></A>
There was Chaos at first, and Darkness, and Night,
			<P CLASS="verse1">
and Tartarus vasty and dismal;
			<P>
But the Earth was not there, nor the Sky, nor the Air,
			<P CLASS="verse1">
till at length in the bosom abysmal
			<P>
Of Darkness an egg, from the whirlwind conceived,
			<P CLASS="verse1">
was laid by the sable-plumed Night.
			<P>
And out of that egg, as the seasons revolved,
			<P CLASS="verse1">
sprang Love, the entrancing, the bright,
			<P>
Love brilliant and bold with his pinions of gold,
			<P CLASS="verse1">
like a whirlwind, refulgent and sparkling!
			<P CLASS="signature">
(Tr. by Rogers, in <I>L. C. L.</I>)
		</DIV></TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note61" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">61</A>
On the exemption of the priests of Egypt from taxation, cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1D*.html#73.5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 73</A>; on the Chaldaeans, cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/2A*.html#29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Book 2.29 f.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note62" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">62</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "of noble sires."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note63" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref63
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">63</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "holders of a share of land."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note64" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">64</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "workers for the people."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note65" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref65
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">65</A>
Called Peteus in <I>Iliad</I> 2.552.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note66" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref66
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">66</A>
There is a break at this point in the text, since what follows can refer only to Cecrops, the traditional first king of Athens, whose body in the lower part was that of a serpent.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note67" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref67
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">67</A>
The Eumolpidae ("Descendants of Eumolpus") and the


<A ID="p95x"></A>Ceryces ("Heralds") were two noble Athenian families, in charge of the more important religious ceremonies of Attica; the <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">pastophoroi</SPAN> were those Egyptian priests who carried in processions small shrines of the gods.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For better details, see the articles
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Eumolpidae.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Eumolpidae
	</A>
and
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Pastophorus.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pastophorus
	</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note68" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref68
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">68</A>
T. Birt (<I>Das antike Buchwesen</I>, pp151 ff.) feels that by this phrase, which is often used by Diodorus, he referred to his


<A ID="p97x"></A>effort to keep the several Books of his history of approximately the same size.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Note:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:pieces_of_Osiris" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1A*.html#ref:pieces_of_Osiris
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
Manuscripts also have "sixteen"; Plutarch
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Isis_and_Osiris*/A.html#T358a
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Isis and Osiris</I>, 358<SPAN CLASS="small">A</SPAN>)
	</A>
says "fourteen".



